The IT Help Desk CLI Toolkit: 2026 Edition
Tags: IT-Support CLI Troubleshooting

GUIs are very good - until they crash and don't work properly. 
When tickets pile up and time is tight, the command line remains the help desk technician's fastest path to resolution. 
Here are the essential CLI tools still powering IT support in 2026.

Network

    ping – Verify basic connectivity and DNS resolution.
    ipconfig / ip addr – Check IP assignment, DHCP status, and adapter config.
    nslookup / dig – Test DNS resolution independent of browser/DoH settings.
    tracert / traceroute – Map network paths to isolate latency or routing failures.
    netstat / ss – Inspect active connections and listening ports for service validation.

System & Performance

    systeminfo / uname -a – Quick OS, version, and hardware overview.
    tasklist / ps – List running processes to identify hangs or resource hogs.
    taskkill / kill – Terminate unresponsive applications remotely or locally.
    getmac / ip link – Retrieve MAC addresses for asset tracking or NAC troubleshooting.

File & Permission Ops

    dir / ls -la – List files with permissions, ownership, and hidden items visible.
    icacls / chmod / chown – Audit or adjust file/folder access rights.
    findstr / grep – Search logs or configs for error codes, timestamps, or keywords.

Remote & Admin

    ssh – Securely access Linux/macOS endpoints or network devices.
    psexec / wmic – Execute commands on remote Windows systems (where policy allows).
    gpresult / get-gpo – Diagnose Group Policy application issues on Windows.

Here are some tips to keep in mind:
    Chain commands with && or | to automate multi-step diagnostics.
    Use | clip (Windows) or | pbcopy (macOS) to pipe output directly to clipboard for ticket notes.
    Save frequent command sets as aliases or PowerShell functions to cut repetitive typing.
    Remember: CLI tools bypass GUI lag and work over low-bandwidth remote sessions—critical for hybrid work support.

Master these, and you'll resolve Tier-1 tickets faster, escalate with better data, and keep your workflow scripting-ready. 
The terminal isn't legacy—it's leverage.
